3.10 Core formulas to remember






ImportantSummary



For the evolution of Erdős–Rényi random graphs G(N,p):

Expected degree: \langle k \rangle = p(N-1)
Giant-component threshold: \langle k \rangle = 1 \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad p_c \approx \frac{1}{N}
Giant-component fraction (self-consistency equation): S = 1 - e^{-\langle k \rangle S}
Near-threshold size: S \approx 2(\langle k \rangle - 1), \qquad \langle k \rangle \downarrow 1^{+}
Connectedness threshold: \langle k \rangle \approx \ln N \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad p \approx \frac{\ln N}{N}

4.10 Core formulas to remember






ImportantSummary



For small-world networks and the Watts–Strogatz model:

Average path length (random network): L(G) \approx \frac{\ln N}{\ln \langle k \rangle}
Lattice distance scaling (d-dimensional): L(G) \sim D(G) \sim N^{1/d}
Ring-lattice average path length: L(0) \approx \frac{N}{2K}
Ring-lattice clustering coefficient: C(0) = \frac{3(K-2)}{4(K-1)}
Small-world regime (\beta small but nonzero): \frac{L(\beta)}{L(0)} \ll 1, \qquad \frac{C(\beta)}{C(0)} \approx 1
Expected clustering in G(N,p): \mathbb{E}[C] = p \ll C(0)
